	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: NES games with sprites smaller than 16 x 16 pixels</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />From old commercial ones, Road Fighter perhaps? Not to mention games with balls, like Pinball or Side Pocket.<br /><br />Some homebrew games also had main characters smaller than 16x16.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Sat Oct 05, 2013 6:39 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: NES games with sprites smaller than 16 x 16 pixels</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />10 Yard Fight and Smash TV have tiny characters (8x16 men). So does Dr. Mario (8x16 or 16x8 pills).<br /><br />If you're including homebrew, Thwaite has tiny people at the bottom, but I guess that's the same issue as Lemmings. Mouser (which doesn't run so well on an NES or a modern emulator due to relying on behaviors now known to be false) has a tiny mouse and tiny cheese, and Snail Maze (which does) has a tiny snail.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


